    "122659675": {
      "title": "An application of Ekeland's theorem to minimax problems",
      "abstract": "IN 1972, Ekeland presented a result [l, Theoreme l] concerning the variational principle and extremum problems of minimization type in complete metric spaces. The result is closely related to ones by BishopPhelps [2], Brondsted-Rockafellar [3], and Brow&r [4]. See [S] for a recent, wide-ranging survey of some of the applications of Ekeland’s Theorem and its variants. Our aim here is to show how Ekeland’s Theorem, or more precisely the augmented form of it provided recently by Rockafellar [6, Theorem 73, can be adapted to extremum problems of minimax type. Elsewhere [7], we give a sharpened form of the present result in the saddle case, that is, the case in which the function defining the minimax problem is convex-concave. These results require a suitable concept of approximate minimax solution. This is introduced below in the form of s-minimax solution. In [7] these are shown to enjoy especially nice properties in the saddle case and that, indeed, they represent the natural notion of approximate solution for such extremum problems. Further use of .s-minimax solutions, in connection with minimax problems not necessarily of saddle type, can be found in [S] and other forthcoming work. In Section 1 we present the main result and several corollaries. In Section 2 we touch on two related issues: minimaximizing sequences, and the plentifulness of subgradients. Throughout. we use the abbreviations w.r.t. (with respect to), 1.s.c. (lower semicontinuous), and us.c. (upper semicontinuous). Finally, whenever it is needed, we adopt the standard convention that +cc (-co) = +co."
